04460nam a22006255i 9780774826891DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748268917 a10.59962/97807748268912doi  a(DE-B1597)661281  a(OCoLC)1175842995  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aHIS0540002bisacsh04a331.341 aMilligan, Ian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRebel Youth :b1960s Labour Unrest, Young Workers, and New Leftists in English Canada /cIan Milligan. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tThe Challenge of Rebel Youth -- tPunching In, Walking Out: The Challenge of Young Workers -- tSay Goodbye to the Working Class? New Leftists Debate Social Change -- tLeaving Campus: The Outward-Looking New Left in Ontario, British Columbia, and Saskatchewan -- tCold, Slogging Solidarity: Supporting Labour on Picket Lines in Ontario and Nova Scotia, 1968–72 -- tA Relationship Culminates: The 1973 Artistic Woodwork Strike -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the "long sixties," baby boomers raised on democratic postwar ideals demanded a more egalitarian society for all. While a few became vocal leaders at universities across Canada, nearly 90% of Canada's young people went straight to work after high school. There, they brought the anti-authoritarian spirit of the youth revolt to the labour movement. While university-based activists combined youth culture with a new brand of radicalism to form the New Left, young workers were pressing for wildcat strikes and defying their aging union leaders in a wave of renewed militancy. In Rebel Youth, Ian Milligan looks at these converging currents, demonstrating convincingly how they were part of a single youth phenomenon. With just short of seventy interviews complementing the extensive use of archival records from ten different cities, this book claims a central place for labour and class in the legacy of the Canadian sixties.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanada -- Social conditions -- 1945-1971. 0aLabor movement -- Canada -- History -- 20th century. 0aLabor movementzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aYoung adults -- Canada -- Social conditions -- 20th century. 0aYoung adults -- Employment -- Canada -- History -- 20th century. 0aYoung adults -- Political activity -- Canada -- History -- 20th century. 0aYoung adultsxEmploymentzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aYoung adultsxPolitical activityzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aYoung adultszCanadaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311141999240uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482689140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774826891423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774826891/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-141999-2  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles